<para id="fs-idm197951232"><link target-id="CNX_Chem_12_05_ArrhPlot"/> is a graph of ln <emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis> versus <m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>T</m:mi></m:mfrac><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> To determine the slope of the line, we need two values of ln <emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis>, which are determined from the line at two values of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>T</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math> (one near each end of the line is preferable). For example, the value of ln <emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis> determined from the line when <m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>T</m:mi></m:mfrac><m:mspace width="0.1em"/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1.25</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>−3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:math> is −2.593; the value when <m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>T</m:mi></m:mfrac><m:mspace width="0.1em"/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1.78</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>−3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:math> is −14.447.</para>
